('C# System.IO Namespace', 'When reading a massive 5GB log file, why is using the static `File.ReadAllText()` method considered a severe architectural anti-pattern compared to using a `StreamReader`?', '`ReadAllText` locks the file permanently, preventing other applications from writing to it.', '`ReadAllText` cannot read files larger than 1GB due to hardcoded OS limitations.', '`ReadAllText` attempts to load the entire 5GB file into the managed heap (RAM) simultaneously, virtually guaranteeing an `OutOfMemoryException`, whereas `StreamReader` reads the file sequentially in small memory chunks.', '`StreamReader` automatically decrypts the file bytes, while `ReadAllText` does not.', 'C', 'Methods like `ReadAllText` or `ReadAllLines` materialize the complete payload in memory at once. For massive files, a `StreamReader` must be used to process the stream in small, manageable buffer sizes, keeping the application''s memory footprint extremely low and preventing crashes.');